<html tal:replace="structure context/manage_page_header"
      tal:define="global entries container/objectValues" />

     <span tal:replace="structure python:container.manage_tabs(help_topic='ObjectManage_Import-Export.stx',
                                                               help_product='OFSP')"/>


     <p class="form-help">
You can export Bastion objects to a local file in order to backup
your Bastion objects prior to performing a new operation - or just
to back up your Bastion object!
     </p>

     <form action="manage_exportObject" method="post">
          <table cellspacing="2" border="0">
              <tr>
                   <td align="left" valign="top">
                        <div class="form-label">
                              Export object id
                        </div>
                    </td>
                    <td align="left" valign="top">
                         <input type="text" name="id" size="25"  class="form-element"
                                value="" tal:attributes="value python:request.form['ids'][0]" tal:on-error="string:"/>
                    </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                   <td align="left" valign="top">&nbsp;</td>
                   <td align="left" valign="top">
                        <div class="form-text">
                            <input type="checkbox" name="toxml" value="Y" /> XML format?
                        </div>
                   </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                   <td></td>
                   <td align="left" valign="top">
                        <div class="form-element">
                            <input class="form-element" type="submit" name="submit" value="Export" />
                        </div>
                   </td>
              </tr>
         </table>
     </form>

     <p class="form-help">
You may import Bastion objects which have been previously
exported to a file (usually .zexp), by selecting that
file from your local file system.
     </p>

     <p class="form-help">
We perform a reasonably thorough check on the import
file to ensure validity, but finally, it IS your responsibility
to ensure that you are doing the right thing, as this IS a 
destructive operation - you WILL lose any contents in your 
current Bastion object!
     </p>

     <p class="form-help">
Note that by default, you will become the owner of the objects 
that you are importing. If you wish the imported objects to retain 
their existing ownership information, select "retain existing 
ownership information".
     </p>

    <form action="manage_importObject" method="post" enctype="multipart/form-data">
       <table cellspacing="2" border="0">
           <tr>
                <td align="left" valign="top">
                     <div class="form-label">Import file name</div>
                </td>
                <td align="left" valign="top">
                     <input type="file" name="upload_file" size="40" value="" />
                </td>
           </tr>
           <tr>

                <td align="left" valign="top">
                    <div class="form-label">Ownership</div>
                </td>
                <td align="left" valign="top">
                    <div class="form-text">
                         <input type="radio" name="set_owner:int" value="1" checked />
                               Take ownership of imported objects
                          <br />
                         <input type="radio" name="set_owner:int" value="0" /> 
                                Retain existing ownership information
                    </div>
                </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
               <td></td>
               <td align="left" valign="top">
                    <div class="form-element">
                          <input type="submit" name="submit" value="Import" />
                    </div>
               </td>
            </tr>
        </table>
    </form>

<html tal:replace="structure context/manage_page_footer"/>




